01:30.324 --> 01:33.226
♪ And they're always
glad you came ♪

01:33.360 --> 01:34.628
♪ ♪

01:34.728 --> 01:36.730
♪ You want to be
where you can see ♪

01:37.230 --> 01:38.632
♪ Our troubles
are all the same ♪

01:38.732 --> 01:39.733
‐ Goo, goo, goo, goo.

01:39.866 --> 01:41.234
‐ ♪ You want to be where ♪

01:41.368 --> 01:43.403
♪ Everybody knows your name ♪
‐ You got a package, Harry.

01:43.537 --> 01:45.405
‐ Bill!
‐ Ah.

01:45.539 --> 01:47.441
‐ ♪ You want to go
where people know ♪

01:47.574 --> 01:50.377
‐ Huh?
‐ ♪ People are all the same ♪

01:50.510 --> 01:52.746
♪ You want to go where
everybody knows your name ♪

01:53.246 --> 01:54.181
‐ No.

01:54.281 --> 01:56.216
[music distorts]
Ah...

01:56.350 --> 01:58.218
♪ ♪

01:58.352 --> 01:59.853
No.

01:59.987 --> 02:03.256
[energy crackling]

02:03.390 --> 02:06.293
[tense music]

02:06.426 --> 02:13.133
♪ ♪

02:17.938 --> 02:19.373
‐ [distorted]
♪ You want to go where ♪

02:19.506 --> 02:20.874
‐ Ah...
‐ ♪ Everybody knows ♪

02:21.008 --> 02:21.875
♪ Your name ♪

02:22.009 --> 02:23.577
♪ ♪

02:23.710 --> 02:26.747
[dog barking]
‐ [snores, gasps]

02:26.880 --> 02:29.750
Evidently, I dream now.

02:29.883 --> 02:30.751
Ah.

02:32.986 --> 02:36.123
[Brown Bird's "Bilgewater"]

02:36.156 --> 02:39.226
[laidback acoustic strumming]

02:39.259 --> 02:41.728
♪ ♪

02:44.831 --> 02:46.366
‐ All right, up and down here.
[indistinct chatter]

02:46.400 --> 02:49.102
[dog barking]

02:49.136 --> 02:50.771
‐ This disruption
is infuriating

02:50.804 --> 02:52.572
and very disrespectful.

02:52.606 --> 02:54.307
How am I supposed to sleep

02:54.341 --> 02:56.176
or bury the dead guy
in my freezer

02:56.209 --> 02:57.544
with all these people
out here?

02:57.577 --> 02:58.779
‐ All right,
let's pick up the pace.

02:58.812 --> 03:00.113
We got to get this stuff
out of here

03:00.147 --> 03:01.515
before the snow hits.

03:01.548 --> 03:05.552
‐ This body needs ten hours
of sleep to function,

03:05.585 --> 03:07.688
and your domesticated wolf
woke it up

03:07.721 --> 03:09.322
before even six hours.

03:09.356 --> 03:10.724
‐ Well, it must suck
to get so much sleep

03:10.757 --> 03:12.793
and still look like shit.
[laughs]

03:12.826 --> 03:14.394
‐ Sorry, Dr. V.

03:14.428 --> 03:16.263
We moved our search
to the shore.

03:16.296 --> 03:18.565
We strongly believe the body
washed up on the beach.

03:18.598 --> 03:20.400
‐ How do you know that?

03:20.434 --> 03:22.669
‐ Because I can feel it...

03:22.703 --> 03:24.337
in my balls.

03:24.371 --> 03:26.707
‐ Well, and I checked
the currents.

03:26.740 --> 03:29.643
So the currents
and the sheriff's balls.

03:29.676 --> 03:31.244
‐ Currents aren't always
accurate,

03:31.278 --> 03:32.813
and you shouldn't
trust your balls.

03:32.846 --> 03:34.848
They're nuts.

03:34.881 --> 03:38.118
‐ [laughing]

03:38.151 --> 03:40.520
‐ Ha‐ha, ha!

03:40.554 --> 03:42.389
I made a joke!
Ha‐ha‐ha!

03:42.422 --> 03:44.458
I made a joke!

03:44.491 --> 03:46.693
[both laughing]

03:46.727 --> 03:48.495
‐ Ha!
Ha‐ha‐ha!

03:48.528 --> 03:50.330
‐ What the shit is that?

03:50.363 --> 03:53.300
[inquisitive music]

03:53.333 --> 03:56.903
♪ ♪

03:56.937 --> 03:59.206
‐ What a lonely species.

03:59.239 --> 04:01.708
Not only did humans
invent dogs for companionship,

04:01.742 --> 04:03.410
they insist
on gathering together

04:03.443 --> 04:05.245
in groups to eat food.

04:05.278 --> 04:09.716
All I need is an empty room,
a spoon, and a pie.

04:09.750 --> 04:11.251
‐ Good news.

04:11.284 --> 04:13.253
We are getting closer
to finding a new town doctor.

04:13.286 --> 04:14.554
I mean, nothing for sure yet.
I just‐‐

04:14.588 --> 04:16.590
I didn't want you to think
that I forgot.

04:16.623 --> 04:18.592
[indistinct chatter]

04:18.625 --> 04:20.861
‐ You're still sitting with me.
‐ Yep.

04:20.894 --> 04:24.631
So I also wanted to ask you
what you are doing tonight.

04:24.664 --> 04:26.333
‐ I was thinking
of chopping up

04:26.366 --> 04:27.834
the body in my freezer.

04:27.868 --> 04:29.202
Spring cleaning.

04:29.236 --> 04:30.270
‐ Ah.

04:30.303 --> 04:31.271
Well, Kate and I
would really like

04:31.304 --> 04:32.506
to have you over
for dinner.

04:32.539 --> 04:34.207
‐ I have food at my house.

04:34.241 --> 04:36.209
‐ Look, um...

04:36.243 --> 04:38.278
we all know that Max
has been having a hard time

04:38.311 --> 04:40.247
with the whole
"you're an alien" thing.

04:40.280 --> 04:41.615
[Harry spits]
Oh. Bless you.

04:41.648 --> 04:44.284
Um, we just thought that maybe
if he could see you

04:44.317 --> 04:45.652
in a more comfortable setting
like our home,

04:45.685 --> 04:48.355
he might not freak out anymore.

04:48.388 --> 04:49.956
So...

04:49.990 --> 04:51.825
we're having you over
for dinner,

04:51.858 --> 04:52.993
and I'm not taking "no"
for an answer.

04:53.026 --> 04:54.327
What do you say?
‐ No.

04:54.361 --> 04:55.495
‐ Na‐na‐na‐na‐na!

04:55.529 --> 04:56.696
And, uh, I heard nothing.

04:56.730 --> 04:58.732
And I will take your silence
as a "yes."

04:58.765 --> 05:00.233
And see you at 6:00.

05:00.267 --> 05:02.936
[country music playing
on jukebox]

05:02.969 --> 05:05.705
♪ ♪

05:05.739 --> 05:06.873
‐ Whoa.

05:06.907 --> 05:08.475
It's a little early,
don't you think?

05:08.508 --> 05:09.576
Honestly, come on.

05:09.609 --> 05:10.977
But I'm down if you're down.

05:11.011 --> 05:12.612
‐ These are the pills
from the party.

05:12.646 --> 05:14.314
They were dated after Sam died.

05:14.347 --> 05:15.982
That means someone
who was there last night

05:16.016 --> 05:17.951
was connected to Sam's
stolen prescription pad.

05:17.984 --> 05:20.654
‐ Hmm. Jay. Obviously.

05:20.687 --> 05:22.823
‐ No. She wouldn't do that.

05:22.856 --> 05:25.525
‐ I'm just saying, she's 17,
so she's...

05:25.559 --> 05:26.927
at least part idiot.

05:26.960 --> 05:29.362
I mean, we did tons
of crazy shit when we were 17.

05:29.396 --> 05:31.865
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ Mostly you.

05:31.898 --> 05:33.366
‐ Me?
‐ Eh...

05:33.400 --> 05:35.769
‐ Oh, I'm pretty sure
that you're the one

05:35.802 --> 05:37.838
that stole
Greg Smith's tractor.

05:37.871 --> 05:39.673
‐ You kidnapped
Len Peazy's fish

05:39.706 --> 05:41.274
and sent a ransom note.

05:41.308 --> 05:44.344
‐ How about
"ceiling fan Olympics"?

05:44.377 --> 05:45.679
Oh!
‐ Drunk ice diving.

05:45.712 --> 05:47.380
‐ Sharpie teardrop tattoo.

05:47.414 --> 05:49.015
‐ Jimmy.

05:49.049 --> 05:51.251
‐ You win.

05:51.284 --> 05:54.020
‐ The mayor asked me to come
to his house tonight

05:54.054 --> 05:55.522
for dinner.

05:55.555 --> 05:57.023
I need you to go
so you can talk to them

05:57.057 --> 05:59.893
and I can sit alone.

05:59.926 --> 06:03.330
‐ That's a little weird,
and I'm busy.

06:03.363 --> 06:05.899
I have to help my dad make
a cake for my niece's birthday.

06:05.932 --> 06:06.933
‐ Mm.

06:06.967 --> 06:09.636
[foot thumps under table]

06:09.669 --> 06:12.639
‐ Maybe D'arcy
would like to go.

06:12.672 --> 06:15.542
‐ I mean, I cou‐‐
[groans] I can't.

06:15.575 --> 06:17.544
I‐I'm just‐‐I'm not free

06:17.577 --> 06:20.480
except for from 5:00
to midnight, so when is it?

06:20.513 --> 06:21.915
‐ 6:00 p. m.
‐ Oh.

06:21.948 --> 06:23.550
Well, there you go.
It's right in there.

06:23.583 --> 06:26.720
Yeah, so you're lucky I'm free.
[chuckles]

06:26.753 --> 06:27.888
‐ I wasn't going to pay you.

06:27.921 --> 06:30.624
That would make you
a prostitute.

06:30.657 --> 06:34.594
‐ [clears throat]
‐ Yeah, I like him.

06:35.795 --> 06:41.501
‐ [scoffs]

06:41.534 --> 06:42.702
[phone rings]

06:42.736 --> 06:43.937
‐ Morning.
‐ Hey.

06:46.039 --> 06:48.541
‐ Oh. [groans]
[Asta chuckles]

06:48.575 --> 06:49.910
‐ I thought you could
use the help.

06:49.943 --> 06:52.412
‐ Mm. Thank you.

06:52.445 --> 06:54.014
Sorry about last night.
‐ Mm‐mm.

06:54.047 --> 06:55.382
‐ I don't know
what got into me.

06:55.415 --> 06:57.517
‐ Nope. No need to explain.

06:57.550 --> 06:58.752
I don't think
there's a house in Patience

06:58.785 --> 07:00.453
I haven't partied at.

07:00.487 --> 07:02.956
‐ Really?
‐ [chuckles]

07:02.989 --> 07:04.057
You know, me and D'arcy,

07:04.090 --> 07:06.626
we used to do
a lot of dumb shit.

07:06.660 --> 07:08.128
‐ Is it true...

07:08.161 --> 07:09.896
she got a speeding ticket
on a stolen tractor?

07:09.930 --> 07:13.066
‐ [laughs]
Yeah.

07:13.099 --> 07:17.837
Also, I stole beer for a guy
from a gas station I worked at.

07:17.871 --> 07:20.607
You ever do anything like that?

07:20.640 --> 07:21.608
‐ What?

07:23.276 --> 07:26.746
‐ Nothing. I just...
[inhales, clears throat]

07:26.780 --> 07:28.081
There were some pills
that were being passed around

07:28.114 --> 07:29.449
at the party last night,

07:29.482 --> 07:31.117
and I think that maybe
they were prescribed

07:31.151 --> 07:33.653
from that missing pad.

07:33.687 --> 07:35.355
‐ Are you being serious
right now?

07:35.388 --> 07:36.456
‐ What?

07:36.489 --> 07:37.791
‐ You think I stole them?

07:37.824 --> 07:39.492
‐ No! Not like‐‐not like that.

07:39.526 --> 07:42.562
‐ Like what, then?
‐ What's going on?

07:42.595 --> 07:44.931
‐ She thinks I stole
the missing prescription pad.

07:44.965 --> 07:46.032
‐ [sighs]

07:46.066 --> 07:47.667
‐ Why would you ask her that?

07:47.701 --> 07:49.970
‐ See?
Even he thinks you're crazy.

07:50.003 --> 07:52.639
‐ Of course she stole it.

07:52.672 --> 07:55.742
Statistically speaking...
it was you.

07:55.775 --> 07:57.644
‐ [scoffs]

07:57.677 --> 07:59.446
‐ I didn't say it. He said it.
‐ This is ridiculous.

07:59.479 --> 08:00.480
‐ Look, I wasn't‐‐
‐ Unbelievable.

08:00.513 --> 08:01.781
‐ Harry.

08:01.815 --> 08:04.851
♪ ♪

08:04.884 --> 08:06.853
No.
That is not yours.

08:06.886 --> 08:08.521
‐ [sniffs]
Mmm.

08:08.555 --> 08:09.823
Mmm.

08:09.856 --> 08:12.959
[quirky music]

08:12.993 --> 08:17.564
♪ ♪

08:18.231 --> 08:21.401
‐ Max, honey.
Can you come in here?

08:28.975 --> 08:31.644
‐ Cookies.
This must be bad.

08:31.678 --> 08:33.646
‐ Your dad and I have something
we want to talk to you about.

08:33.680 --> 08:35.882
‐ I knew this day
was gonna come,

08:35.915 --> 08:40.420
and I just want you to know
I'm okay with it.

08:40.453 --> 08:41.821
‐ You are?

08:41.855 --> 08:43.056
‐ Yeah.

08:43.089 --> 08:44.891
I'll live with Dad
Monday to Wednesday

08:44.924 --> 08:47.060
and every other weekend,

08:47.093 --> 08:48.762
and I'm with Mom
on Thanksgivings,

08:48.795 --> 08:50.230
'cause she can cook turkey.

08:50.263 --> 08:53.099
‐ Wait, wait. You think that
we're getting a divorce?

08:53.133 --> 08:55.168
‐ It's okay.
Love is fleeting.

08:55.201 --> 08:58.038
‐ Honey, we aren't
getting a divorce.

08:58.071 --> 09:00.140
‐ We just want to tell you
that Dr. Vanderspeigle

09:00.173 --> 09:01.708
is coming to dinner tonight.

09:01.741 --> 09:04.177
‐ What? No!

09:04.210 --> 09:07.514
Why can't you just be
getting a divorce?

09:09.182 --> 09:11.051
[Max screams]
‐ [sighs]

09:16.089 --> 09:18.758
‐ Max for Sahar.
Come in, Sahar. Over.

09:18.792 --> 09:20.593
[walkie‐talkie beeps]

09:20.627 --> 09:22.095
‐ Sahar here. Over.

09:22.128 --> 09:23.830
‐ I just wanted to say goodbye.

09:23.863 --> 09:25.632
My life is over. Over.

09:26.900 --> 09:28.835
‐ What do you mean,
"It's over‐over"?

09:28.868 --> 09:30.203
Over.

09:30.236 --> 09:32.739
‐ My parents invited the alien
over for dinner,

09:32.772 --> 09:34.240
so I'm dead soon.

09:34.274 --> 09:36.242
‐ This is great news!

09:36.276 --> 09:37.777
‐ What?

09:37.811 --> 09:39.746
‐ We talked about wanting
to get into his cabin

09:39.779 --> 09:41.614
to look around, right?

09:41.648 --> 09:43.716
I've got a plan. Over.

09:46.586 --> 09:47.921
‐ What are they cooking
for dinner?

09:47.954 --> 09:50.090
Actually, don't tell me.
I want it to be a surprise.

09:50.123 --> 09:51.758
[chuckles]
Maybe it's surf and turf.

09:51.791 --> 09:53.193
‐ She's clueless.

09:53.226 --> 09:54.394
She has no idea this dinner

09:54.427 --> 09:57.730
will just be a kid screaming
and throwing food at me.

09:57.764 --> 10:00.066
[dog barking
in the distance]

10:02.569 --> 10:04.938
‐ Dr. Vanderspeigle!

10:04.971 --> 10:06.773
How good to see you!

10:06.806 --> 10:08.675
[curious music]

10:08.708 --> 10:11.144
‐ Mm, smells like meatloaf.

10:11.177 --> 10:13.079
It's just turf,
but I'll take it.

10:13.113 --> 10:14.214
[chuckles]

10:14.247 --> 10:20.553
♪ ♪

10:26.626 --> 10:28.862
‐ ♪ It's like
I've always known... ♪

10:29.829 --> 10:29.863
‐ Okay, can you put the wine
on the table?

10:30.163 --> 10:31.297
‐ Yep.

10:31.331 --> 10:33.099
‐ D'arcy, I‐‐
‐ Hello!

10:33.133 --> 10:35.068
‐ I'm‐‐I'm so glad you came!

10:35.101 --> 10:37.003
Oh!
‐ You are.

10:37.036 --> 10:39.305
‐ Honey, you didn't tell me
Harry was bringing a date.

10:39.339 --> 10:40.773
‐ Well, I had no idea.

10:40.807 --> 10:42.108
‐ This is a date?

10:42.142 --> 10:43.676
‐ Uh, pump the brakes.
We just met.

10:43.710 --> 10:45.445
But, yes,
this is a thing now.

10:45.478 --> 10:47.447
He said it was a date first
before I did,

10:47.480 --> 10:48.715
and now he's like,
"Which is it?"

10:48.748 --> 10:50.717
Which is crazy because he's...

10:50.750 --> 10:52.318
very into me.

10:52.352 --> 10:54.521
‐ Welcome. We're just so happy
that you joined us.

10:54.554 --> 10:56.923
‐ Yes. Uh, deviled eggs?

10:56.956 --> 10:59.592
‐ [gasps]
[dog barking in the distance]

10:59.626 --> 11:02.128
[suspenseful music]

11:02.162 --> 11:05.632
‐ His pockets are empty.
No house keys. Over.

11:05.665 --> 11:07.967
‐ He probably uses mind control
to unlock doors.

11:08.001 --> 11:10.603
‐ Or he can shapeshift
his fingers into a key.

11:10.637 --> 11:12.639
Over.
‐ What are we gonna do? Over.

11:12.672 --> 11:14.007
‐ I don't know. Over.

11:14.040 --> 11:16.643
‐ Think! Over.
‐ Thinking! Over.

11:16.676 --> 11:20.647
♪ ♪

11:20.680 --> 11:22.081
Check his truck. Over.

11:22.115 --> 11:28.988
♪ ♪

11:40.400 --> 11:41.734
[horn honks]

11:41.768 --> 11:44.003
‐ Shoot!

11:44.037 --> 11:45.705
Sorry, Allah.

11:51.578 --> 11:53.046
‐ Max, dinner's ready.

11:53.079 --> 11:59.953
♪ ♪

12:03.856 --> 12:05.992
Well, this is nice.

12:06.025 --> 12:07.527
Isn't this nice, Max?

12:07.560 --> 12:09.862
‐ Yep. I'm having a great time.

12:09.896 --> 12:13.066
‐ What is
this little shitbag up to?

12:13.099 --> 12:15.768
‐ So, uh,
Dr. Vanderspeigle, um...

12:15.802 --> 12:16.903
actually, you know what?

12:16.936 --> 12:18.671
I'm just‐‐
I'm gonna call you Harry.

12:18.705 --> 12:20.073
I mean,
we're all friends here, right?

12:20.106 --> 12:22.075
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ Mm.

12:22.108 --> 12:23.710
‐ So, Harry, tell us
a little bit about yourself.

12:23.743 --> 12:25.778
Where are you from?

12:28.114 --> 12:29.916
‐ New York City.

12:29.949 --> 12:31.217
‐ Mm! Oh, my God.
‐ Mm.

12:31.251 --> 12:32.819
‐ Mm‐hmm. Yes.
[Kate groans]

12:32.852 --> 12:34.654
‐ I've always wanted
to live there.

12:34.687 --> 12:35.688
What is it like?

12:35.722 --> 12:37.824
‐ New York has...

12:38.891 --> 12:40.860
It has law.

12:40.893 --> 12:42.929
And it has order.

12:42.962 --> 12:44.230
‐ Mm.

12:44.264 --> 12:47.600
‐ There are police
who investigate the crimes,

12:47.634 --> 12:51.638
and there are
district attorneys who...

12:51.671 --> 12:54.240
prosecute the offenders.
‐ Mm‐hmm.

12:54.274 --> 12:56.743
‐ It has women
who have sex in the city.

12:56.776 --> 12:58.011
‐ Hot.

12:58.044 --> 12:59.979
‐ Uh‐‐well, um...

13:00.013 --> 13:02.915
after Max goes off to college,

13:02.949 --> 13:04.817
Ben and I are going
to move there.

13:04.851 --> 13:06.886
‐ Really?
‐ News to me.

13:06.919 --> 13:09.689
‐ Oh, I just thought you would
want to try something new.

13:09.722 --> 13:11.724
I mean, you've lived here since
you were a kid. [chuckles]

13:11.758 --> 13:15.461
‐ We've both lived here
since, like, forever.

13:15.495 --> 13:18.131
Hey, Max, I've known your dad

13:18.164 --> 13:20.266
since we were both
younger than you.

13:20.300 --> 13:21.834
How about that?
What are you, like, 13?

13:21.868 --> 13:24.137
‐ He's nine.
‐ Oh! Kindergartener.

13:24.170 --> 13:25.838
Right?
‐ Mm, fourth grade.

13:25.872 --> 13:26.906
‐ Whatever.
‐ Yep.

13:26.939 --> 13:28.107
‐ You're cute.
‐ Yeah.

13:28.141 --> 13:30.476
D'arcy and I sat right next
to each other

13:30.510 --> 13:31.944
in Ms. Philworth's class.

13:31.978 --> 13:35.114
‐ Oh. Mrs. Philworth.
‐ Mm.

13:35.148 --> 13:36.716
‐ She was a farty‐party.

13:36.749 --> 13:38.785
[both chuckle]
Remember that?

13:38.818 --> 13:41.054
Just like...
[laughs] Instantly.

13:41.087 --> 13:43.222
‐ [laughs] It was horrible.
[D'arcy laughs]

13:43.256 --> 13:45.491
‐ D'arcy, I had no idea you two
were so close growing up.

13:45.525 --> 13:47.226
‐ Oh, yeah, I mean, in fact,

13:47.260 --> 13:50.630
Ben‐‐Benny was my first kiss.

13:50.663 --> 13:52.131
[laughs]

13:52.165 --> 13:54.300
‐ Benny never mentioned that.

13:54.334 --> 13:56.769
‐ I'm sure I did at some point.
‐ Nope. You didn't.

13:56.803 --> 13:58.137
‐ Huh.
‐ Yeah.

13:58.171 --> 13:59.772
It was the last year
of fifth grade.

13:59.806 --> 14:01.507
Very romantic.

14:01.541 --> 14:05.044
As I recall, I don't think
we ever officially broke up.

14:05.078 --> 14:06.079
‐ Oh, my God.

14:06.112 --> 14:07.313
This whole time,

14:07.347 --> 14:08.715
I've been cheating on you
with Kate.

14:08.748 --> 14:10.149
‐ How dare you?
‐ I don't know!

14:10.183 --> 14:11.184
[all laugh]

14:11.217 --> 14:12.652
‐ I'm gonna get
some more salad.

14:12.685 --> 14:14.520
‐ More wine too.
You bitch. [laughs]

14:14.554 --> 14:17.056
‐ Be right back.

14:17.090 --> 14:18.624
Right on that.
[clears throat]

14:18.658 --> 14:19.892
‐ Mr. Henderson...

14:19.926 --> 14:22.128
‐ Yeah, I'd like
to get a refund...

14:22.161 --> 14:25.198
‐ Great. Line of old people
and the po‐po.

14:25.231 --> 14:28.101
[indistinct chatter]

14:30.870 --> 14:33.673
‐ You cut in front
of that little girl.

14:33.706 --> 14:34.807
‐ What are you talking about?
I'm with you.

14:34.841 --> 14:35.975
We buying evidence bags.

14:36.008 --> 14:37.744
This is official
sheriff's business.

14:37.777 --> 14:40.113
‐ You're buying
a Hot Wheels car.

14:40.146 --> 14:43.049
‐ This isn't just a Hot Wheel.
This is a '65 Mustang.

14:43.082 --> 14:44.350
What am I supposed to do?
Not buy it?

14:44.384 --> 14:45.685
Then what?

14:45.718 --> 14:46.919
Some kid buys it,
they take it home,

14:46.953 --> 14:47.987
and, playing with it
in their driveway,

14:48.020 --> 14:48.955
the thing goes out
into the street.

14:48.988 --> 14:49.989
They run after it.

14:50.022 --> 14:50.990
The next thing you know,

14:51.023 --> 14:53.092
a city bus plows
right into 'em.

14:53.126 --> 14:56.696
Not on my watch.
Mm‐mm.

14:56.729 --> 14:58.765
‐ He collects them.
‐ Don't talk to me.

15:00.600 --> 15:02.702
I'm buying tampons
and I'm embarrassed about it.

15:02.735 --> 15:06.205
[suspenseful music]

15:06.239 --> 15:07.707
‐ Okay, put in your PIN.

15:07.740 --> 15:09.575
‐ [sighs]

15:09.609 --> 15:11.811
‐ Well, the dinner's
a success, huh?

15:11.844 --> 15:13.079
Isn't it great

15:13.112 --> 15:15.047
how well Max and the doctor
are getting along?

15:15.081 --> 15:16.315
‐ I just think
it's a little weird

15:16.349 --> 15:19.852
you never told me
you made out with D'arcy.

15:19.886 --> 15:21.020
I mean, what?

15:21.053 --> 15:22.822
Did you think
I'd be mad or something?

15:22.855 --> 15:24.157
‐ Mad? You?

15:24.190 --> 15:26.225
[scoffs]
What? No.

15:26.259 --> 15:28.327
It's just‐‐it's not a big deal.

15:28.361 --> 15:30.062
It was fifth grade.

15:30.096 --> 15:32.598
‐ It is so cool that you guys
bought your parents' house.

15:32.632 --> 15:34.100
‐ Oh, yeah, yep.

15:34.133 --> 15:36.002
Uh, we are very lucky.

15:36.035 --> 15:37.236
‐ Yeah.
‐ Mm‐hmm.

15:37.270 --> 15:38.971
‐ Just like‐‐remember when
we were sitting

15:39.005 --> 15:40.373
on the couch that one time,

15:40.406 --> 15:43.142
dreaming about how this
could be our house one day?

15:43.176 --> 15:45.244
‐ Oh, yeah, yeah.
A million years ago.

15:45.278 --> 15:47.413
‐ Wow, that is looking ahead
for a fifth grader.

15:47.447 --> 15:49.916
‐ Mm.
Yeah, this was in tenth grade.

15:49.949 --> 15:51.117
We dated
in tenth grade too.

15:51.150 --> 15:52.251
[chuckles]

15:52.285 --> 15:54.220
‐ Really?
‐ Yes. Oh, yeah.

15:54.253 --> 15:56.622
Taught this guy
everything he knows.

15:56.656 --> 15:57.957
[laughs]
‐ [chuckles]

15:57.990 --> 15:59.992
Well, not‐‐not everything.

16:00.026 --> 16:02.929
‐ Yes! You're welcome, okay?
[chuckles]

16:02.962 --> 16:04.430
I'm gonna grab this.
‐ Thanks.

16:04.464 --> 16:05.631
Yeah.

16:05.665 --> 16:07.767
‐ Hmm.

16:07.800 --> 16:08.768
‐ What are you doing?

16:08.801 --> 16:10.336
Why are you being so nice
to me?

16:10.369 --> 16:12.104
I tried to kill you two times.

16:12.138 --> 16:13.940
Wait.

16:13.973 --> 16:15.408
Cut your head off
with a bone saw,

16:15.441 --> 16:16.375
tried to kill you
in your sleep,

16:16.409 --> 16:18.077
cut your brakes so that
you'd die in traffic.

16:18.110 --> 16:20.112
Three times. I've tried
to kill you three times.

16:20.146 --> 16:21.113
‐ You didn't mean it.

16:21.147 --> 16:22.348
‐ Yes.

16:22.381 --> 16:24.283
Yeah‐‐no, I did.
I looked forward to it.

16:24.317 --> 16:26.752
I was even planning
on eating some of you

16:26.786 --> 16:28.054
to see what humans tasted like.

16:28.087 --> 16:29.088
‐ You know what?

16:29.121 --> 16:30.756
I think I'd do the same thing

16:30.790 --> 16:32.425
if I were an alien.

16:32.458 --> 16:34.260
I'll be we taste
like pot roast.

16:34.293 --> 16:35.962
‐ [grunts]
‐ More potatoes?

16:35.995 --> 16:38.965
[inquisitive music]

16:38.998 --> 16:41.968
♪ ♪

16:41.968 --> 16:44.971
[machine whirring]

16:45.004 --> 16:48.107
[indistinct chatter]

16:48.140 --> 16:51.110
‐ You keep tapping those hands,
you're gonna lose 'em.

16:51.143 --> 16:57.984
♪ ♪

16:58.017 --> 17:00.953
‐ Max, come on back.
We're finishing dessert.

17:00.987 --> 17:04.223
‐ Well, it was so nice
having you here.

17:04.257 --> 17:06.826
You should take home
some leftovers.

17:06.859 --> 17:08.494
‐ I'll take the rest
of the cookies

17:08.528 --> 17:10.162
and these seven bananas.

17:10.196 --> 17:12.164
‐ Wait.
They can't leave yet.

17:12.198 --> 17:14.166
I want to show them
my solar system!

17:14.200 --> 17:16.469
‐ Oh, I don't know, honey.
It's‐‐it's getting late.

17:16.502 --> 17:17.970
‐ Please?

17:18.004 --> 17:19.372
‐ Well, you know,
maybe‐‐maybe just quickly.

17:19.405 --> 17:21.173
I mean, they're getting along
so well.

17:21.207 --> 17:22.875
‐ Come on, yeah.

17:22.909 --> 17:24.076
Who doesn't love
a show‐and‐tell?

17:24.110 --> 17:26.846
Probably need a nightcap,
though, if we're gonna do that.

17:26.879 --> 17:28.180
[laughs]
Kate‐O, top me off?

17:28.214 --> 17:29.348
Come on!

17:29.382 --> 17:31.050
Come on! Love you, girl.

17:31.083 --> 17:33.719
New York City.
There we go.

17:33.753 --> 17:35.388
‐ And me and my dad
made it together.

17:35.421 --> 17:36.789
Isn't it great?

17:40.560 --> 17:42.895
‐ Actually, yes.

17:42.929 --> 17:44.196
It's pretty accurate.

17:44.230 --> 17:46.132
‐ Yeah, he even used
tiny marbles

17:46.165 --> 17:47.533
for the two moons of Mars.

17:47.567 --> 17:49.335
‐ That's not a moon.
That's a transit station.

17:49.368 --> 17:51.404
[all laugh]
‐ [laughs awkwardly]

17:51.437 --> 17:52.939
‐ The blue one is Uranus,

17:52.972 --> 17:54.173
in case you didn't know.
‐ Oh, yeah.

17:54.206 --> 17:55.341
I heard a lot of assholes
live there.

17:55.374 --> 17:57.343
[both laugh]

17:57.376 --> 18:02.081
‐ [laughing breathlessly]

18:02.114 --> 18:04.550
I told a joke earlier too.

18:04.584 --> 18:07.353
The sheriff's balls
are also his nuts!

18:07.386 --> 18:09.922
[cackling]

18:09.956 --> 18:11.324
‐ [chuckles]

18:11.357 --> 18:14.060
‐ Okay, I‐‐you know, I think
it's probably time

18:14.093 --> 18:15.995
for us to go to bed‐‐
‐ No, no, no! He can't go yet!

18:16.028 --> 18:18.230
I want...

18:18.264 --> 18:20.499
to read them my book report
about "The Giver"!

18:20.533 --> 18:22.034
‐ Ooh!
‐ Ooh.

18:22.068 --> 18:24.103
‐ I'm game. [chuckles]
I love "The Giver."

18:24.136 --> 18:27.106
Bit of a giver, myself.
[chuckles]

18:27.139 --> 18:29.075
[Max clears throat]

18:29.108 --> 18:32.078
[dramatic music]

18:32.111 --> 18:38.417
♪ ♪

18:38.451 --> 18:41.787
‐ "And using his gift
to see beyond,

18:41.821 --> 18:44.557
"he finds a sled and rides it
down to a Christmas house."

18:44.590 --> 18:46.258
‐ [snoring]

18:46.292 --> 18:48.060
‐ "The end."

18:48.094 --> 18:50.596
‐ Mm. Ha.
‐ Hmm. Wow.

18:50.630 --> 18:52.298
‐ Incredible story.
‐ All right.

18:52.331 --> 18:54.533
I think it is past
somebody's bedtime.

18:54.567 --> 18:57.403
Maybe two people's.

18:57.436 --> 19:00.439
Harry, it was so lovely
having you.

19:00.473 --> 19:03.442
And, D'arcy, you...
were here too.

19:03.476 --> 19:05.077
‐ Thank you.
‐ Yeah.

19:05.111 --> 19:06.812
Let's do this again
sometime soon.

19:06.846 --> 19:08.347
‐ Yeah.
Like when, exactly?

19:08.381 --> 19:09.482
[giggles]

19:09.515 --> 19:11.050
‐ Just, uh...

19:14.186 --> 19:17.056
‐ I know. You too.
‐ Yup.

19:17.089 --> 19:19.392
‐ Don't go!
‐ Mm!

19:19.425 --> 19:21.627
‐ Let him go, buddy, now.

19:21.661 --> 19:23.229
‐ All right.
‐ Max, now.

19:23.262 --> 19:24.597
Now.

19:24.630 --> 19:25.564
Ben, could you take him,
please?

19:25.598 --> 19:26.465
‐ No!
‐ Come on.

19:26.499 --> 19:28.100
‐ Oh! Okay.

19:28.134 --> 19:30.136
‐ See you around, sister wife.

19:30.169 --> 19:31.337
[laughs]
Come on, girl.

19:31.370 --> 19:33.606
Mm.
[D'arcy groans]

19:33.639 --> 19:35.007
Mm.

19:35.041 --> 19:37.143
‐ Okay.

19:37.176 --> 19:38.978
‐ Whoa!
[grunts]

19:39.011 --> 19:41.180
[dog barking in the distance]

19:41.213 --> 19:44.183
[tense music]

19:44.216 --> 19:50.222
♪ ♪

19:52.425 --> 19:55.194
‐ I'm starting to think
the kid's not faking.

19:55.227 --> 19:57.163
He actually likes me.

19:57.196 --> 19:59.632
And why wouldn't he?
I'm a likable alien.

19:59.665 --> 20:06.639
♪ ♪

20:06.672 --> 20:09.208
[keys jingle]

20:11.410 --> 20:14.447
[engine turns over]

20:14.480 --> 20:15.681
‐ [sighs]

20:15.715 --> 20:19.685
♪ ♪

20:19.719 --> 20:20.920
Yes!

20:22.288 --> 20:25.157
[romantic music
playing on radio]

20:25.191 --> 20:32.031
♪ ♪

20:32.064 --> 20:34.033
‐ ♪ It's too soon
to say goodbye ♪

20:34.066 --> 20:35.301
‐ This is your home.

20:35.334 --> 20:38.070
♪ ♪

20:38.104 --> 20:41.373
‐ Are you gonna kiss me?

20:41.407 --> 20:44.343
‐ I've seen this on TV.

20:44.376 --> 20:45.377
I can do this.

20:45.411 --> 20:47.146
Mm...

20:47.179 --> 20:49.448
‐ ♪ I'm just saying,
it's a shame to part ♪

20:49.482 --> 20:51.050
‐ Mm.

20:51.083 --> 20:52.618
‐ ♪ It's too soon
to say goodbye ♪

20:52.651 --> 20:53.919
‐ [grunts]

20:53.953 --> 20:56.288
‐ [grunting]

20:56.322 --> 20:59.191
‐ ♪ Don't you know
I'm not the kind ♪

20:59.225 --> 21:01.160
‐ [grunts]

21:01.193 --> 21:04.396
‐ ♪ Tie you up
or tie you down ♪

21:04.430 --> 21:07.733
‐ It's‐‐it's not the worst...
kiss I've ever had.

21:07.767 --> 21:14.473
♪ ♪

21:15.775 --> 21:17.109
‐ [shouts excitedly]

21:17.143 --> 21:19.945
[suspenseful music]

21:19.979 --> 21:22.948
It's rigor mortis!

21:22.982 --> 21:25.317
My penis is dying!

21:30.990 --> 21:33.826
[curious music]

21:34.193 --> 21:34.994
♪ ♪

21:35.027 --> 21:36.428
‐ Hey, you're early.

21:36.462 --> 21:37.997
‐ Your grandmother called.

21:38.030 --> 21:39.965
Her back's hurting again.

21:39.999 --> 21:42.001
You think we can bring her
one of those steroid shots

21:42.034 --> 21:43.402
like Sam used to give her?

21:43.435 --> 21:45.371
‐ Um, sure,

21:45.404 --> 21:48.541
although we need a doctor
to administer the shot.

21:48.574 --> 21:50.409
And Harry's on call
this afternoon.

21:50.442 --> 21:52.578
So he can just go with us.
‐ I don't want him to go.

21:52.611 --> 21:54.313
‐ I don't want to go.

21:54.346 --> 21:56.649
‐ Well, I don't want men
to act like children.

21:56.682 --> 21:58.751
So I guess none of us
get what we want.

22:01.353 --> 22:03.856
Excuse me.

22:03.889 --> 22:05.424
‐ Take note.

22:05.457 --> 22:06.926
We got no body yet,

22:06.959 --> 22:09.028
but this lake definitely
is holding some clues.

22:09.061 --> 22:12.364
Now, all of these items here,
this here,

22:12.398 --> 22:14.033
this could all be linked
to the death.

22:14.066 --> 22:16.802
‐ And don't forget this.

22:16.836 --> 22:18.904
‐ Yeah,
I don't think so, deputy.

22:18.938 --> 22:22.775
‐ Sir, a doorknob in the lake‐‐
that's not exactly normal.

22:22.808 --> 22:24.877
‐ Normal? Oh, okay.

22:24.910 --> 22:26.946
Let me ask you something.
Pop quiz, deputy.

22:26.979 --> 22:28.848
Can a boat sink?

22:28.881 --> 22:31.417
‐ Yes.
‐ Is a houseboat a boat?

22:31.450 --> 22:32.952
‐ Yep.
‐ Houseboats have doors?

22:32.985 --> 22:35.554
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ Do doors have knobs?

22:35.588 --> 22:37.056
‐ Yeah.

22:37.089 --> 22:39.658
‐ See? Completely common
to find a doorknob in a lake.

22:39.692 --> 22:41.493
Write that down.

22:41.527 --> 22:43.495
Cletus know that.

22:43.529 --> 22:44.630
Don't you, boy?

22:44.663 --> 22:46.465
You know that, don't you?
Yes, you do!

22:46.498 --> 22:47.733
Who's my favorite deputy?

22:47.766 --> 22:49.702
Who's the best deputy
in the world?

22:49.735 --> 22:51.704
You are!
You're the cutest deputy!

22:51.737 --> 22:53.472
What are you doing
with those paws?

23:00.713 --> 23:04.383
‐ Hmm.
This is interesting.

23:04.416 --> 23:07.653
I've never
experienced this before.

23:07.686 --> 23:10.923
Nobody is talking.

23:10.956 --> 23:12.992
Apparently you can be
with other humans

23:13.025 --> 23:15.794
and still be alone.

23:15.828 --> 23:18.664
I like it.

23:18.697 --> 23:23.135
I can feel the happiness
welling up inside me.

23:23.168 --> 23:24.837
I need to pee.

23:24.870 --> 23:31.744
♪ ♪

23:39.551 --> 23:41.520
‐ That cowboy's
a pretty good writer.

23:41.553 --> 23:43.088
‐ He was a pretty good writer.

23:43.122 --> 23:46.125
And then you killed him.
You remember?

23:46.158 --> 23:48.160
‐ Don't look at me.

23:48.193 --> 23:50.829
According to the local paper,
it was a simple robbery.

23:50.863 --> 23:53.699
I hear violence is up
in America's rural areas. Hmm.

23:55.968 --> 23:57.670
‐ What's wrong with you?

23:57.703 --> 23:59.805
Our orders are
to find the alien that crashed,

23:59.838 --> 24:01.907
not to go around
murdering people!

24:01.941 --> 24:04.209
‐ Our orders are to deliver
an alien to the general

24:04.243 --> 24:05.978
without anyone
knowing about it.

24:06.011 --> 24:07.846
So, yeah,
things are gonna get messy.

24:07.880 --> 24:09.949
I mean, you're acting as if
we can just sit here

24:09.982 --> 24:13.452
and the alien's
going to come to us.

24:13.485 --> 24:14.787
Let me sum this up for you.

24:14.820 --> 24:16.889
I'm eliminating anything

24:16.922 --> 24:20.092
that gets in the way
of this mission...

24:20.125 --> 24:22.494
which might be you
if you don't stop whining.

24:22.528 --> 24:25.230
So shut the ‐‐‐‐ up.

24:25.264 --> 24:31.136
♪ ♪

24:31.170 --> 24:33.572
[door opens, slams]

24:33.605 --> 24:40.479
♪ ♪

24:44.249 --> 24:47.786
‐ [shivers]

24:47.820 --> 24:50.155
Do you shiver when you pee?

24:53.025 --> 24:55.294
‐ Sometimes.

24:55.327 --> 24:56.895
‐ Good.

24:58.030 --> 24:59.631
Oh! It's‐‐

25:00.799 --> 25:02.901
[chuckles]
This is good.

25:02.935 --> 25:04.870
[zipper closes]

25:09.908 --> 25:12.945
[door closes]

25:12.978 --> 25:15.781
[upbeat rock music]

25:15.814 --> 25:22.688
♪ ♪

25:30.996 --> 25:34.133
‐ Hey, they're here!
‐ Dan and Asta!

25:34.166 --> 25:35.901
‐ Hey, Dan.
‐ There they are.

25:35.934 --> 25:39.638
♪ ♪

25:39.671 --> 25:41.974
‐ Hi.
‐ Welcome.

25:42.007 --> 25:44.076
‐ Hi.
‐ Auntie Asta.

25:44.109 --> 25:45.577
[both smooch]

25:45.611 --> 25:47.980
‐ I'm so happy to see you.

25:48.013 --> 25:49.615
‐ Hi, Uncle.
‐ Hi, guys!

25:49.648 --> 25:52.217
‐ Hi, sweetie.
[smooches]

25:52.251 --> 25:54.153
Oh, the little man,
he's getting so big.

25:54.186 --> 25:55.654
‐ [laughs]
I know.

25:55.687 --> 25:57.656
‐ Oh, you remember Harry
from the clinic.

25:57.689 --> 25:59.158
He's been helping
since Sam's passing.

25:59.191 --> 26:00.926
He's gonna help
with Grandma's back.

26:00.959 --> 26:03.095
‐ Oh, I'm so sorry about Sam.
‐ Yeah.

26:03.128 --> 26:04.663
‐ Nice to have you, Harry.

26:04.696 --> 26:07.332
‐ I had no choice.
She forced me to come.

26:07.366 --> 26:09.301
‐ I like this one.

26:09.334 --> 26:11.136
Let me know
if you want something to drink.

26:11.170 --> 26:12.604
I have soda, juice.

26:12.638 --> 26:14.206
We have some fancy water
that tastes like static.

26:14.239 --> 26:17.676
‐ Do you have any milk
that comes from a cow's teat?

26:17.709 --> 26:19.178
‐ Wow.

26:19.211 --> 26:21.013
‐ He takes
some getting used to.

26:21.046 --> 26:22.981
‐ Happy to have you, Harry.
‐ This is my husband, Shane.

26:23.015 --> 26:24.850
‐ Mm.

26:24.883 --> 26:26.885
‐ Welcome, Harry.

26:26.919 --> 26:28.987
[warm music]

26:29.021 --> 26:33.592
‐ I see now it's not the food
that brings humans together.

26:33.625 --> 26:36.228
It's each other.

26:36.261 --> 26:39.198
There is a basic human need
to feel like you belong.

26:39.231 --> 26:40.299
‐ Hi!

26:40.332 --> 26:42.668
‐ It feels...

26:42.701 --> 26:43.802
good.

26:49.341 --> 26:53.112
‐ Gee, I thought you guys
got lost on your walk here.

26:54.179 --> 26:55.447
‐ Sorry, Mom.
We had to stop at the bathroom.

26:55.481 --> 26:59.351
‐ Whose tiny bladder?
[laughs]

26:59.384 --> 27:00.986
‐ Gram,
this is Dr. Vanderspeigle.

27:01.019 --> 27:02.754
He's gonna give you your shot.

27:02.788 --> 27:04.089
I know you liked Sam,

27:04.123 --> 27:05.424
but you're in good hands
with Harry.

27:05.457 --> 27:07.759
‐ Of course I am.

27:07.793 --> 27:10.229
I've never met a white man
I couldn't trust!

27:10.262 --> 27:12.231
[laughs]
‐ Hmm.

27:12.264 --> 27:14.032
Let me help you up.

27:16.969 --> 27:18.203
‐ [grunts]

27:18.237 --> 27:21.206
[suspenseful music]

27:21.240 --> 27:28.347
♪ ♪

27:28.380 --> 27:31.350
[siren wails]
‐ Pull it over to the curb.

27:31.383 --> 27:34.119
[siren wailing]

27:34.153 --> 27:35.787
‐ What the heck?

27:35.821 --> 27:39.958
♪ ♪

27:39.992 --> 27:42.461
Follow my lead.
‐ [mouths word]

27:42.494 --> 27:44.263
‐ Keep your hands
on the handlebars

27:44.296 --> 27:46.231
where I can see 'em.

27:46.265 --> 27:47.933
[bell rings]

27:49.835 --> 27:51.203
Do you know
why I pulled you over?

27:51.236 --> 27:54.940
‐ Speed?
‐ Boredom?

27:54.973 --> 27:56.208
‐ Took a left turn back there

27:56.241 --> 27:58.076
without using
your hand signals.

27:58.110 --> 27:59.111
What the heck
are you kids doing

27:59.144 --> 28:00.913
so far out of town,
anyway, huh?

28:00.946 --> 28:02.481
‐ We heard Bigfoot
was on the loose.

28:02.514 --> 28:03.582
‐ Bigfoot‐‐
what you talking about?

28:03.615 --> 28:07.085
Everybody know that
damn Bigfoot up in Seattle.

28:07.119 --> 28:08.887
That's...

28:08.921 --> 28:11.423
Sorry about cussing
just then. I...

28:11.456 --> 28:13.358
try not to do that shit
around kids.

28:13.392 --> 28:14.960
‐ It's okay.

28:14.993 --> 28:17.196
I'm not allowed to say
the D word or the S word,

28:17.229 --> 28:18.964
but I can hear them
without getting in trouble.

28:18.997 --> 28:20.098
‐ That's cool.

28:20.132 --> 28:21.266
I do like the fact
that you kids

28:21.300 --> 28:22.901
are outdoors
and not stuck inside

28:22.935 --> 28:24.503
with your face glued
to some screen.

28:24.536 --> 28:26.271
That's good.
All right.

28:26.305 --> 28:27.940
Y'all go have fun.
Be safe.

28:27.973 --> 28:29.107
Get that reflector fixed

28:29.141 --> 28:30.542
and get yourself
some all‐weather tires.

28:30.576 --> 28:32.277
And next time,
you use your hand signals.

28:32.311 --> 28:34.246
You know
how the saying goes, right?

28:34.279 --> 28:36.281
If you don't use your arms
to signal,

28:36.315 --> 28:39.284
a truck'll rip 'em right off.

28:39.318 --> 28:41.520
True story.

28:41.553 --> 28:44.456
All right, be safe.

28:44.489 --> 28:47.292
‐ I can say the D word.
[overenunciating] Damn.

28:47.326 --> 28:49.194
‐ Cool.
[car door opens, closes]

28:49.228 --> 28:52.231
[soft music]

28:52.264 --> 28:56.034
♪ ♪

28:56.068 --> 28:58.237
[door closes]

28:58.270 --> 29:00.572
‐ I have one rule in here.

29:00.606 --> 29:02.307
That's if you're gonna
start drinking,

29:02.341 --> 29:04.576
you have to make sure
your gun isn't loaded.

29:04.610 --> 29:06.578
‐ Oh, I'm fine.

29:06.612 --> 29:08.313
Just one of those days
where you question

29:08.347 --> 29:10.549
whether you deserve to exist.

29:10.582 --> 29:11.950
‐ And you're gonna need
something stronger

29:11.984 --> 29:13.051
than lemonade.

29:13.085 --> 29:14.519
‐ When you were
in the Olympics,

29:14.553 --> 29:16.321
do you know where I was?

29:16.355 --> 29:17.889
‐ In home ec,
learning to sew?

29:17.923 --> 29:19.491
‐ The day you skied
for the gold medal,

29:19.524 --> 29:21.827
I was sitting right here
in this same stool.

29:21.860 --> 29:23.228
It was packed.

29:23.262 --> 29:25.597
Everyo‐‐I mean,
everyone in town

29:25.631 --> 29:27.499
was in here,
cheering you on.

29:27.532 --> 29:29.534
[moody country music playing
on speakers]

29:29.568 --> 29:31.603
‐ Well, thanks, Liv.

29:31.637 --> 29:34.273
I'm sorry all I brought back
is a shattered leg.

29:34.306 --> 29:35.607
‐ Are you kidding?

29:35.641 --> 29:37.342
You're one
of the best damn skiers

29:37.376 --> 29:39.211
to ever come out of Colorado.

29:39.244 --> 29:41.280
[door opens]

29:41.313 --> 29:43.348
‐ It was so long ago.
[door closes]

29:43.382 --> 29:46.018
Sometimes I forget that I ever
did anything, you know?

29:46.051 --> 29:48.020
‐ You put Patience on the map.

29:48.053 --> 29:51.223
How many people can say that?

29:51.256 --> 29:53.925
I've never been that good
at anything.

29:53.959 --> 29:56.295
‐ Is this
a Sheriff Mike spiral again?

29:56.328 --> 29:58.497
‐ You had a whole country
cheering for you.

29:58.530 --> 30:01.366
And I just need one person.
Just one.

30:01.400 --> 30:03.602
He makes me feel so dumb.

30:03.635 --> 30:08.206
‐ Listen, you are the best cop
Patience has ever had.

30:08.240 --> 30:09.975
You're the only cop
I've ever met

30:10.008 --> 30:11.376
that people are actually
excited to see.

30:11.410 --> 30:12.644
‐ Hmm.

30:12.678 --> 30:14.246
‐ You treat everybody fairly.

30:14.279 --> 30:16.381
And you always
do the right thing.

30:16.415 --> 30:18.216
So do right by yourself

30:18.250 --> 30:20.385
and go stand up
to that power trip.

30:20.419 --> 30:23.255
Trust me, you're the best thing
that's ever happened to him.

30:23.288 --> 30:26.124
If he can't see that,
then that's his loss.

30:26.158 --> 30:27.292
‐ Thanks.

30:27.326 --> 30:29.127
‐ Yeah.

30:29.161 --> 30:33.999
♪ ♪

30:34.032 --> 30:36.501
‐ Jesus.
D'arce, I'm on duty.

30:36.535 --> 30:38.003
‐ Yeah, me too.

30:38.036 --> 30:40.172
Started at 11:00, so...
‐ [scoffs]

30:40.205 --> 30:42.607
‐ Let's get this show
on the road, Doc.

30:42.641 --> 30:44.242
I've got a tail feather
to shake.

30:44.276 --> 30:45.677
‐ You literally can't walk.

30:45.711 --> 30:47.946
‐ Can someone put this one
in time‐out?

30:47.979 --> 30:50.115
She keeps me prisoner in here.

30:50.148 --> 30:51.616
‐ Maybe it's for our own good.

30:51.650 --> 30:54.586
‐ Hey, Dan, give me that belt
so I can whip ya.

30:54.619 --> 30:55.987
[Kayla scoffs]
‐ [laughs]

30:56.021 --> 30:57.322
Jeez, Mom.

30:59.191 --> 31:00.525
‐ Go ahead.
I'm tough.

31:05.731 --> 31:08.166
‐ We're done.

31:08.200 --> 31:09.668
‐ Whew.

31:09.701 --> 31:11.436
‐ You should feel
some numbness,

31:11.470 --> 31:13.372
but in about 15 minutes,

31:13.405 --> 31:15.440
you should feel good enough
to whip Dan.

31:15.474 --> 31:19.444
‐ [laughs]
Well, I can laugh without pain.

31:19.478 --> 31:22.414
That's a good sign.
[chuckles]

31:22.447 --> 31:25.250
You're here to do good things,
my boy.

31:25.283 --> 31:26.351
I can tell.

31:26.385 --> 31:28.353
[baby fussing]

31:28.387 --> 31:30.355
[soft music]

31:30.389 --> 31:33.225
‐ Oh, come here.

31:33.258 --> 31:35.360
Okay.
‐ Gonna go.

31:35.394 --> 31:38.230
‐ It's about time you have
one of your own, honey.

31:38.263 --> 31:40.465
‐ I don't know
about all that, Gram.

31:40.499 --> 31:43.201
‐ She already
has one of her own.

31:43.235 --> 31:45.103
A 17‐year‐old girl named Jay.

31:47.072 --> 31:48.607
‐ What?
‐ What?

31:48.640 --> 31:50.642
‐ Jay at the clinic.

31:50.675 --> 31:53.111
That's Asta's daughter.

31:53.145 --> 31:55.647
It's very obvious you have
the same facial structures,

31:55.680 --> 31:58.216
and you both eat like
you're starving to death.

31:58.250 --> 31:59.985
‐ I'm‐‐

32:00.018 --> 32:02.020
I'm sorry.

32:02.053 --> 32:03.655
[tense music]

32:03.688 --> 32:05.490
‐ Ah! Ah!

32:05.524 --> 32:08.493
And they both run out of rooms
when they get emotional.

32:08.527 --> 32:10.595
♪ ♪

32:15.534 --> 32:19.371
‐ ♪ Coming down
from the mountain ♪

32:20.138 --> 32:23.642
♪ Burn a trouble fountain ♪

32:23.675 --> 32:29.815
♪ Right away you asked me
what is wrong ♪

32:29.848 --> 32:32.384
‐ [sighs]

32:32.417 --> 32:34.319
‐ ♪ I couldn't say ♪
[Kayla grunts]

32:34.352 --> 32:37.155
♪ I didn't know the problem ♪

32:37.189 --> 32:39.157
‐ [sighs]
You're easy to find

32:39.191 --> 32:42.661
but a pain in the ass
to get to.

32:42.694 --> 32:44.930
‐ How bad
did I mess this one up?

32:44.963 --> 32:46.698
‐ [sighs]

32:46.731 --> 32:48.934
Well...

32:48.967 --> 32:50.569
you gave up your kid

32:50.602 --> 32:53.905
only to stalk her till she was
old enough to work for you.

32:53.939 --> 32:55.841
You haven't told your dad
that he's been serving pancakes

32:55.874 --> 32:57.676
to his granddaughter.

32:57.709 --> 33:00.178
[sighs] And Jay's probably
been wondering her whole life

33:00.212 --> 33:01.346
who she is,

33:01.379 --> 33:05.917
only to be staring at you
in the face every day at work.

33:05.951 --> 33:07.686
‐ That's pretty bad.

33:07.719 --> 33:09.821
‐ I'm not gonna lie.

33:09.855 --> 33:11.690
You kept up
a really big secret,

33:11.723 --> 33:14.693
and it's gonna hurt a lot
of people when it comes out.

33:14.726 --> 33:18.230
[melancholy music]

33:18.263 --> 33:21.733
‐ I couldn't take care of her.
I was just a kid myself.

33:23.301 --> 33:26.972
‐ I know.
‐ [cries]

33:27.005 --> 33:28.707
‐ [sighs] You made
a really difficult decision

33:28.740 --> 33:30.709
at a really young age.

33:30.742 --> 33:32.911
And I admire that about you.

33:35.247 --> 33:36.848
‐ You do?
‐ Yeah.

33:36.882 --> 33:43.755
♪ ♪

33:45.957 --> 33:49.628
‐ You put Jay's needs
ahead of your own.

33:49.661 --> 33:51.763
And that's exactly
what a mother does.

33:51.796 --> 33:55.901
♪ ♪

33:55.934 --> 33:57.869
‐ [crying]
Okay.

34:00.539 --> 34:04.676
[indistinct chatter]

34:04.709 --> 34:07.012
‐ Oh, man!
‐ That's all right.

34:07.045 --> 34:08.380
‐ Over here!
‐ Box him out!

34:12.284 --> 34:13.318
[basketball slams]
‐ Got it!

34:13.351 --> 34:14.553
‐ Oh!
‐ Over here.

34:14.586 --> 34:15.687
‐ Here you go!

34:18.290 --> 34:19.758
‐ My bad, bro.

34:19.791 --> 34:21.726
Can you toss that ball
back to us?

34:28.266 --> 34:29.334
‐ Over here!

34:32.804 --> 34:34.439
‐ Whoa!
‐ Damn, Harry!

34:34.472 --> 34:35.707
Can you hoop?

34:35.740 --> 34:38.476
[applause]
‐ Hoop!

34:38.510 --> 34:41.713
‐ ♪ Hey! Hey! ♪

34:41.746 --> 34:44.683
♪ Hey! Hey! ♪

34:44.716 --> 34:47.519
♪ Hey! Hey! ♪

34:47.552 --> 34:49.688
♪ Hey! Hey! ♪

34:49.721 --> 34:52.657
[upbeat electronic music]

34:52.691 --> 34:55.493
♪ ♪

34:55.527 --> 34:58.597
‐ You got to dribble.
‐ Do it, come on.

34:58.630 --> 35:01.399
‐ What are you doing, bro?
Shoot or pass the ball!

35:01.433 --> 35:03.435
I'm on your team!
I'm wide open!

35:03.468 --> 35:05.070
‐ Ball hog.

35:05.103 --> 35:07.072
‐ ♪ Hey! Hey! ♪

35:07.105 --> 35:09.708
♪ ♪

35:11.843 --> 35:14.813
[suspenseful music]

35:14.846 --> 35:21.753
♪ ♪

35:39.537 --> 35:40.605
‐ Shh.

35:40.639 --> 35:45.510
♪ ♪

35:45.543 --> 35:47.612
‐ Take this.

35:47.646 --> 35:49.648
Oh.

35:49.681 --> 35:56.588
♪ ♪

36:01.893 --> 36:03.628
What does this guy eat?

36:06.798 --> 36:10.001
[geese honking]

36:10.035 --> 36:12.704
[cow moos in the distance]

36:18.677 --> 36:22.881
‐ How could you not tell me
Jay was the girl?

36:24.649 --> 36:26.685
[solemn music]

36:26.718 --> 36:28.887
‐ Why would I?

36:28.920 --> 36:30.855
You wouldn't understand.

36:30.889 --> 36:33.124
You wanted me out the second
that you knew I was pregnant.

36:33.158 --> 36:34.893
‐ Is that what
you tell yourself?

36:34.926 --> 36:37.395
You left, Asta.

36:37.429 --> 36:38.930
No one ever told you to go.

36:38.963 --> 36:41.099
‐ You hated Jimmy.

36:41.132 --> 36:44.169
‐ Well, I hated the way
he treated you.

36:44.202 --> 36:47.539
And then you just ran off
with him.

36:47.572 --> 36:49.040
You know, we all expected

36:49.074 --> 36:50.909
a baby to come home
with you that day.

36:50.942 --> 36:53.445
‐ It wasn't any of your
business what I did with her.

36:53.478 --> 36:55.413
‐ You were 16!

36:55.447 --> 36:57.048
Of course it was my business.

36:59.851 --> 37:03.455
‐ What was I supposed to do?

37:03.488 --> 37:06.091
Take my baby to class?

37:06.124 --> 37:09.828
Raise her in Jimmy's bedroom
at his mom's house?

37:09.861 --> 37:12.731
♪ ♪

37:12.764 --> 37:14.532
‐ You know...

37:14.566 --> 37:16.501
look around you.

37:16.534 --> 37:19.771
We all would've been there
for you, especially me.

37:21.773 --> 37:23.942
‐ I couldn't do that to you.

37:23.975 --> 37:26.578
♪ ♪

37:26.611 --> 37:28.813
You already raised one child
that wasn't your own.

37:28.847 --> 37:31.216
I didn't want mine to be
one more problem for you.

37:31.249 --> 37:33.451
‐ Who wants cake?

37:33.485 --> 37:39.691
♪ ♪

37:39.724 --> 37:42.894
‐ Are we gonna be okay?

37:42.927 --> 37:45.897
‐ Even when we're not okay,
we'll always be okay.

37:45.930 --> 37:52.804
♪ ♪

37:54.906 --> 37:58.510
[footsteps descending stairs]

38:00.011 --> 38:01.913
‐ Wow.

38:01.946 --> 38:04.983
[suspenseful music]

38:05.016 --> 38:11.956
♪ ♪

38:11.990 --> 38:14.592
Maybe these are parts
of his ship.

38:14.626 --> 38:17.228
‐ Check this out.

38:17.262 --> 38:19.230
There must be something
in this freezer.

38:19.264 --> 38:20.632
Why else would it be locked?

38:20.665 --> 38:23.234
[lock rattling]

38:23.268 --> 38:29.507
♪ ♪

38:29.541 --> 38:30.608
‐ Sahar!

38:30.642 --> 38:37.048
♪ ♪

38:38.183 --> 38:39.517
‐ Whoa!

38:45.557 --> 38:47.625
‐ Come on! Hey!
‐ Over here, over here!

38:48.193 --> 38:49.661
[indistinct chatter]

38:49.694 --> 38:51.596
[lively music]

38:51.629 --> 38:53.865
‐ Hoop! Hoop!

38:53.898 --> 38:56.401
Goal! Hoop! Hoop!

38:56.434 --> 38:58.970
‐ You just scored
for the other team!

38:59.003 --> 39:02.006
♪ ♪

39:02.040 --> 39:04.442
‐ How are they still running?

39:04.475 --> 39:07.445
Are they cyborgs?

39:07.478 --> 39:10.348
I am done.

39:10.381 --> 39:11.649
Tired.

39:11.683 --> 39:15.353
‐ Come on, man.
We're still playing.

39:15.386 --> 39:16.821
‐ Oh, come on!

39:16.855 --> 39:18.656
Where you going, bro?

39:18.690 --> 39:20.758
We need you on D!

39:20.792 --> 39:22.293
Harry!

39:22.327 --> 39:23.928
‐ I am overheating.

39:23.962 --> 39:25.897
Is this how it ends?

39:25.930 --> 39:27.932
[tense music]

39:27.966 --> 39:31.402
[breathing heavily]

39:34.906 --> 39:37.876
[ethereal music]

39:37.909 --> 39:40.411
Home.

39:40.445 --> 39:43.848
My sun hasn't changed
since I've been on Earth.

39:43.882 --> 39:47.719
It's still
46 light‐years away.

39:47.752 --> 39:50.722
But it feels different.

39:50.755 --> 39:53.858
It feels closer...

39:53.892 --> 39:55.827
like a single string
could pull me up

39:55.860 --> 39:57.896
from my chest to the sky.

39:57.929 --> 40:02.967
♪ ♪

40:03.001 --> 40:05.003
‐ The boys said
you couldn't hang.

40:08.039 --> 40:10.074
‐ They are
incredible specimens.

40:10.108 --> 40:13.578
‐ [chuckles]

40:13.611 --> 40:15.780
[soft piano music]

40:15.813 --> 40:17.582
Hmm.

40:17.615 --> 40:24.489
♪ ♪

40:33.831 --> 40:37.468
My dad says that the stars
in the Big Dipper

40:37.502 --> 40:41.940
are seven brothers,
shot into the sky like arrows.

40:41.973 --> 40:45.543
♪ ♪

40:45.576 --> 40:48.446
‐ Am I supposed to apologize?

40:48.479 --> 40:51.883
♪ ♪

40:51.916 --> 40:53.818
‐ You could.

40:55.720 --> 40:59.023
‐ I'm sorry for telling
your secret about Jay.

40:59.057 --> 41:03.461
♪ ♪

41:03.494 --> 41:05.530
‐ You did us a favor.

41:07.799 --> 41:09.367
‐ I miss home.

41:11.669 --> 41:13.938
‐ Do you have family there?

41:13.972 --> 41:15.606
‐ A...

41:15.640 --> 41:17.909
wife.

41:17.942 --> 41:20.578
She died.

41:20.611 --> 41:24.682
So I took a job
that brought me here.

41:24.716 --> 41:27.151
[sighs]
I want to go home.

41:27.185 --> 41:29.387
I belong there.

41:29.420 --> 41:30.855
‐ I'm sorry.

41:33.524 --> 41:35.660
That's so sad.

41:35.693 --> 41:37.061
‐ Yes.

41:39.430 --> 41:41.065
It is now.

41:41.099 --> 41:47.972
♪ ♪

41:49.774 --> 41:51.642
Everyone needs to belong

41:51.676 --> 41:54.979
to something bigger
than themselves.

41:55.013 --> 41:57.115
Yes, there is strength
in numbers,

41:57.148 --> 42:00.852
but maybe it's simpler.

42:00.885 --> 42:03.554
Maybe humans just feel better
when they know

42:03.588 --> 42:06.924
they are not alone
on this Earth.

42:06.958 --> 42:09.560
‐ ♪ We them bougie Natives ♪

42:09.594 --> 42:11.062
‐ ♪ Hold my knowledge
in my braids ♪

42:11.095 --> 42:12.764
‐ ♪ We them bougie Natives ♪

42:12.797 --> 42:14.565
‐ ♪ New cedar, new sweetgrass,
new sage ♪

42:14.599 --> 42:15.600
♪ We them bougie Natives ♪
‐ ♪ Bougie Natives ♪

42:15.633 --> 42:17.568
‐ [laughing]

42:17.602 --> 42:19.504
‐ ♪ Look, snow goonie
from the boonies ♪

42:19.537 --> 42:21.039
♪ Not the type you see
in movies ♪

42:21.072 --> 42:22.640
♪ Felt the spirit
living through me ♪

42:22.673 --> 42:24.175
♪ Since I was a puny dookie ♪

42:24.208 --> 42:25.710
♪ Neechie, neechie,
lookie, lookie ♪

42:25.743 --> 42:26.878
♪ How I get low
when I boogie ♪

42:26.911 --> 42:27.879
‐ What?
‐ ♪ Don't mind me ♪

42:27.912 --> 42:29.213
♪ Some goodie‐goodies ♪

42:29.247 --> 42:30.581
♪ I'm Nate and bougie ♪

42:30.615 --> 42:32.050
♪ My wifey be the wolf ♪

42:32.083 --> 42:33.551
♪ And I'm the wolf
that's from the sea ♪

42:33.584 --> 42:34.886
♪ And she no Pocahontas ♪

42:34.919 --> 42:36.187
♪ More like
Buffy Sainte‐Marie ♪

42:36.220 --> 42:37.955
